# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 3x3-basketball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:3x3-basketball/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:3x3-basketball/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:3x3-basketball/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:3x3-basketball/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:3x3-basketball/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:3x3-basketball/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:3x3-basketball/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:3x3-basketball/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:3x3-basketball/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:3x3-basketball/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:3x3-basketball/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:3x3-basketball/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:3x3-basketball/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:3x3-basketball/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:3x3-basketball/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:3x3-basketball/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:3x3-basketball/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:3x3-basketball/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:3x3-basketball/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:3x3-basketball/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:3x3-basketball/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:3x3-basketball/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:3x3-basketball/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:3x3-basketball/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:3x3-basketball/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:3x3-basketball/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:3x3-basketball/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:3x3-basketball/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:3x3-basketball/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:3x3-basketball/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:3x3-basketball/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:3x3-basketball/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:3x3-basketball/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:3x3-basketball/2007-asian-indoor-games] The **2007 Asian Indoor Games** (Chinese: 2007年亞洲室內運動會; Portuguese: *Jogos Asiáticos em Recinto Coberto de 2007*), officially known as the **2nd Asian Indoor Games** and also known as **Macau 2007**, were held in Macau, China from 26 October 2007 to 3 November 2007.
[src:3x3-basketball/2007-asian-indoor-games] Most events of the games took place at the Macao East Asian Games Dome.
[src:3x3-basketball/2007-asian-indoor-games] The Emblem of the 2nd Asian Indoor Games gives an overall impression of the sun shining above the covered gymnasium.
[src:3x3-basketball/2007-asian-indoor-games] There were 44 Asian countries confirmed to participate in the games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2007-asian-indoor-games] A total of 17 sports were scheduled to be competed in this edition of the Indoor Asiad.
[src:3x3-basketball/2007-asian-indoor-games] The following is a list of the sports and the number of the designated events in parentheses.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] The plan for the Asian Youth Games was part of Singapore's bid to stage the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics (YOG).
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] The purpose was to allow youths to use the chance to benchmark their performances against youth teams from Asian nations.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] The Games also provided Singapore with an opportunity to test organisational and logistical capabilities in advance of the 2010 YOG.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] The organisation of the Games, spearheaded by the Singapore Sports Council, cost S$15 million, which was part of the $130 million for YOG.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] The 1st Asian Youth Games torch relay started on 28 June morning with the *Community and Corporate Leg*.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] The flame lighting ceremony was held on 28 June at the Kallang Waterfront.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] The flame is then carried across the island in buses to arrive at the start of the three routes, named after the Olympic values of Friendship, Excellence and Respect.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] A total of 70 torchbearers were involved in day one of the relay.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] The torch relay resumed on 29 June for the *Schools leg*, with the flame travelling to 45 schools around Singapore, where over a hundred runners had the honour of carrying the torch.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] The relay ended at the Singapore Indoor Stadium where three athletes ran in with the torches and light the cauldron as part of the Opening Ceremony celebrations.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] The theme song entitled *Asia's Youth, Our Future* was unveiled on 19 March 2009.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] The song carries the message of hope and friendship and was composed by musician Iskandar Ismail, and written jointly by Jose Raymond and Hoo Cher Liek.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] The singers are Nathan Hartono and Lian Kim Selby.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] The official emblem of the 2009 Asian Youth Games was unveiled on 14 November 2008 and designed by Brainwave Design.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] The logo, as described by Olympic Council of Asia, represents excellence and victory that the athletes will bring during the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] Many countries' postal services have also released stamps, such as Uzbekistan.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] The sports events were broadcast 'live' primarily via the official website through 4 concurrent 'live' streams during the games period.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] It was the first multi-sport event to receive approval from the Olympic Council of Asia to provide broadcast coverage of all the sports events completely via digital channels.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] Singapore's television channel, MediaCorp Channel 5 provided daily highlights of the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] StarHub TV had 4 dedicated TV channels to provide coverage for the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] The opening ceremony was broadcast 'live' via the website.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] In addition, Video On-Demand Clips capturing key sporting highlights of the various games were made available.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] The Asian Youth Games and the 2010 Summer Youth Olympic Games are expected to use the same competition venues.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] NTUC Downtown East originally was the planned Games Village for athletes and officials.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] However, a decision was made to move the Games Village to central Singapore at Swissotel The Stamford.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] The change was made as NTUC Downtown East does not have enough beds for the athletes.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] Due to the H1N1 outbreak, Swissotel The Stamford catered the ninth floor to suspect cases in athletes.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] Themed *Asia's Youth, Our Future*, the inaugural Asian Youth Games opening ceremony on 29 June was held in the Singapore Indoor Stadium.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] More than 1,400 performers from 20 schools and tertiary institutions took part in the opening ceremony.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] The opening ceremony was graced by Singapore Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] Representatives from the Olympic Council of Asia and the Singapore National Olympic Council were also present.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] There were three segments which were showcased: 'Asia's Zest', 'Garden in the City', and 'Spirit Of Evolution'.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] The AYG cauldron was lit by three Singaporean young athletes, Tao Li (swimming), Remy Ong (bowling), and Jasmine Ser (shooting).
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] The Singapore Asian Youth Games 2009 saw an estimated 1,300 athletes aged between 14 and 17 from 43 countries competing in more than 80 sporting events.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] Attempts were made to stage all 26 YOG sports but, due to time and resource constraints, Singapore and the Olympic Council of Asia trimmed it to nine.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] There were a total of 9 sports, the 8 that the Singapore and the Olympic Council of Asia trimmed down from the 26 YOG sports as well as an addition sport of Bowling which is not an official Olympics Sport.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] On 19 June, a member of the Philippines football team came down with H1N1 flu, causing the Group A football preliminary match between Philippines and Chinese Taipei due to be played at Meridian Junior College on the same day to be suspended till further notice.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] Four cases of H1N1 flu virus were discovered from the Hong Kong football team on 22 June.
[src:3x3-basketball/2009-asian-youth-games] Malaysia has withdrawn most of its athletes (with the exception of their sailors) due to concerns over the H1N1 outbreak.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The **2010 Summer Youth Olympics**, officially known as the **I Summer Youth Olympic Games**, and commonly known as **Singapore 2010**, were the inaugural edition of the Youth Olympic Games (YOG), an Olympic Games-based event for young athletes.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Held in Singapore from 14 to 26 August 2010, it was the first International Olympic Committee–sanctioned event held in Southeast Asia.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The Games featured about 3,600 athletes aged 14–18 from 204 nations, who competed in 201 events in 26 sports.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] No official medal tables were published, but the most successful nation was China, followed by Russia; host Singapore did not win any gold medals.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Most features that are unique to the YOG, such as mixed-NOCs teams (comprising youths from different countries) and the Culture and Education Programme (CEP), made their debut at the 2010 Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Although the concept dates back to 1998, formal plans for the YOG were only first announced at the 119th IOC session on 6 July 2007.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] On 21 February 2008, Singapore was selected as the host city after defeating Moscow 53–44 in a postal vote by 105 International Olympic Committee (IOC) members.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The Singapore Youth Olympic Games Organising Committee (SYOGOC) prepared eighteen competition venues and twelve training venues.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The Float@Marina Bay hosted the opening and closing ceremonies and the Youth Olympic Village was located at Nanyang Technological University (NTU).
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The committee also selected Games mascots Lyo and Merly (a lion and a female merlion), the Spirit of Youth emblem (through a design competition) and the theme song "Everyone", performed by five singers representing each major continent, combining North and South America.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Online media, Asian newspapers and 166 television broadcasters provided extensive coverage of the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The torch relay, which began on 23 July 2010, comprised a thirteen-day world tour of five cities, each representing a continent, and a six-day domestic leg.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Highlights of the opening and closing ceremonies include performances about Singaporean history and culture, a 32-metre (35 yd) Olympic cauldron, flags being brought onto stage and items featuring YOG symbols.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The Games were marred by discrepancies in the budget and attendance figures, two wrestlers caught doping, a walkover in the taekwondo final and allegations that Bolivian footballers were overage.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The concept of the YOG was developed in 1998 by Johann Rosenzopf in response to concerns over childhood obesity and declining youth participation in sports.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] IOC President Jacques Rogge formally announced plans for the YOG at the 119th IOC session in Guatemala City on 6 July 2007.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Singapore, which had hosted the 117th session, made its first formal bid to host a multi-disciplinary sporting event of this magnitude.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Positive factors in its bid included its high connectivity with the world, its youthfulness as an independent country, and its positive reputation for excellence and multiracial harmony.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The city-state rolled out a high-publicity campaign which included being amongst the first to launch its official website, bid logo (despite IOC rules against bid logos) and a bid tagline "Blazing the Trail" on 16 October 2007.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] It also got the local population to support its bid, including an effort by students to collect 1 million signatures.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Eleven cities expressed interest in hosting the Games, nine of which ultimately applied.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Five cities amongst the nine were selected for the shortlist: Athens (Greece), Bangkok (Thailand), Moscow (Russia), Singapore, and Turin (Italy).
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The list was further shortened to two finalists, Singapore and Moscow.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] On 21 February 2008, Rogge announced that Singapore had won the postal vote 53–44 and was thus selected as the host for the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] There were concerns over whether two new venues that had been planned – a Youth Olympic Village and an equestrian complex – would be ready in time for the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] A construction expert believed the US$423 million plan for an Olympic Village at the National University of Singapore (NUS) was feasible, and that the equestrian venue could be delivered on time.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] In spite of the expert's findings, the Youth Olympic Village at the NUS's University Town did run into difficulties owing to increasing construction costs.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] It was subsequently decided that existing student halls of residence at Nanyang Technological University in Jurong West would be used for the Olympic Village.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The Singapore Youth Olympic Games Organising Committee (SYOGOC) was tasked with organising the inaugural Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] It was aided by a panel of advisors composed of Cabinet ministers and Senior Parliamentary Secretary Teo Ser Luck.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] In addition, an Inter-Ministry Committee was established with Niam Chiang Meng, Permanent Secretary, Ministry of Community Development, Youth and Sports as its chairman.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Singapore also received some international support for the Games preparations.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The People's Republic of China, host of the 2008 Summer Olympics, expressed its desire to assist Singapore in its preparations.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Sebastian Coe, Lord Coe, Chairman of the London Organising Committee for the 2012 Summer Olympics, announced that members of his organising team, including coaches and administrators, planned to attend the event.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The Bid Committee secured 4,310 guaranteed rooms in 36 hotels.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The official hotel partner for the Games was Fairmont Singapore.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The IOC initially projected in 2007 that the Youth Olympic Games would cost US$30 million to stage.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Singapore won its bid in 2008 with a budget of US$75.5 million (S$105 million) with strong government support.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The budget was later increased to U$284 million (S$387 million), thrice the original amount, which the organisers attributed to major revisions in the scope and scale of the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Costs were increased for logistics and transport, security, and upgrades of various sports venues and technology.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Financially, local companies received about 70%, or S$260 million, worth of contracts from the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Concerns over cost overruns were dismissed by SYOGOC Chairman Ng Ser Miang.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The cost overruns was to become an issue that was raised by opposition parties during Singapore's 2011 general elections.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Eighteen competition venues were used at the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Events took place at 11 pre-existing venues, one new venue (the Singapore Turf Club Riding Centre), and six temporary venues that will be removed following the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Twelve venues were also set aside for training purposes.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Certain venues such as the Singapore Indoor Stadium and The Float@Marina Bay were temporarily converted to host sports events, while Kallang Field was upgraded to be able to host the archery competition.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The Float@Marina Bay, a floating stage, was the main stadium for the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Capable of seating 25,000 spectators, it hosted the opening ceremony on 14 August, was a venue for the cycling event, and also hosted the closing ceremony held on 26 August 2010.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] All competition and non-competition venues were within 30 minutes of the Youth Olympic Village, the Main Media Centre (MMC) and the Olympic Family Hotels (OFH).
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] An Event Transport Operations Centre (ETOC) managed all transport matters relating to the YOG, providing real-time travel information.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] A shuttle service linked all YOG venues for all accredited persons, who were also entitled to complimentary travel on public buses and the Mass Rapid Transit system.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Youth Olympic Lanes were designated along key routes for faster access to all YOG venues.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The Youth Olympic Village (YOV) of the Games housed over 5,000 athletes and team officials for 18 days from 10 to 28 August 2010.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Located in Nanyang Technological University (NTU), the YOV served as accommodation and a preparation point for the Games, and also hosted specially designed cultural and educational activities for athletes.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] On 7 June, it was announced that Parliamentary Secretary and SYOGOC advisor Teo Ser Luck, former national sprinter Canagasabai Kunalan and former national swimmer Joscelin Yeo had been appointed as the Village Mayor and Deputy Village Mayors respectively.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Plans for the Youth Olympic torch relay, dubbed the Journey of the Youth Olympic Flame (JYOF), were unveiled on 26 January 2010.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The torch used was 60 cm (24 in) high, 5 to 8 centimetres (2.0 to 3.1 in) wide, and weighed 0.74 kg (1.6 lb).
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The flame was lit at Olympia in Greece on 23 July 2010 and travelled to five cities representing the continents Asia, Africa, Europe, Oceania and the Americas.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] After spending 13 days on its world tour, the torch relay continued for another six days in Singapore.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] A portable cauldron at the Marina Bay Promenade was lit by Minister Mentor Lee Kuan Yew on 13 August at the end of the torch relay in Singapore.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The opening ceremony of the Games was held on 14 August at The Float@Marina Bay, a floating stage near downtown Singapore.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Approximately 27,000 spectators attended the event, which took place against a backdrop of the city's skyline.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Event tickets cost between S$30 and S$200.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The show, the largest ever held by the city, involved over 750 hours of rehearsals.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Over 7,000 performers, mostly under the age of 18, took part in the ceremony.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] At the centre of the stage was the 32-metre (35 yd) tall Olympic cauldron designed by Randy Chan as a lighthouse.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] It was flanked by six giant LED displays, which stood behind a reflecting pool containing 200 t (7,100,000 oz) of water.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Prime Minister of Singapore Lee Hsien Loong was present at the event.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Following pre-show warm-up and a countdown led by children and young drummers, the show began proper at 20:10 hrs (UTC+8)—a reference to the year of the event—with a fireworks show, followed by a cultural segment titled "*Selamat Datang*" that featured Chinese, Malay and Indian performers.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The segment ended with performances by homegrown artistes of Eurasian and Peranakan heritage, symbolising the mixture of tradition and modernity in Singapore.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Audience members were greeted with pre-recorded messages from several Olympic ambassadors: Olympians Usain Bolt, Michael Phelps and Yelena Isinbayeva, members of the band Thirty Seconds to Mars, and actors Jackie Chan and Jet Li.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] During the "Origins" segment on the city's history, performers entered the stage in freight containers to depict the arrival of the earliest immigrants.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The ceremony continued with a dance performance featuring popular songs from the 1940s to the present era.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] A segment entitled "Monster" told the story of a young boxer who had to fight a giant monster.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] He summons his Silat warriors to fight against the monster, but they failed, as well as when he summons his Kalari warriors and Wushu warriors.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] But soon he overcomes his inner fears and defeats the giant monster.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Singer Seah Wei Wen then performed "Across The Finish Line" composed by Mayuni Omar & Mathilda D Silva, in the centre of the reflecting pool.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] It was followed by "Playing with Fire", which featured the dragon as a symbol of courage, strength and wisdom.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] In this segment, 500 youth from Soka Gakkai Singapore participate to form from many fishes into a dragon.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Reflecting the theme of global co-operation, members of the World Youth Orchestra of the Singapore Games performed an orchestral piece featuring various instruments from around the world.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The orchestra was led by Darrell Ang, the young associate conductor of the Singapore Symphony Orchestra.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The following segment, titled "Bud", depicted rain as a symbol of hope and rejuvenation.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Ending the show segment of the ceremony were singers Marcus Lee of Ex-Dee and Lian Kim Selby, performing the song "A New Story", which was commissioned for the event.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Their performance was accompanied by a fashion show organized by students from LASALLE College of the Arts.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Each flag of the National Olympic Committees represented was brought on stage by an athlete representative.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Following Olympic tradition, the flag of Greece entered first as the originator of the games, and the flag of Singapore entered last as the host nation.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The flag ceremony was followed by the singing of the Games theme song and remarks by Ng Ser Miang, Chairman of the Singapore Youth Olympic Games Organising Committee, and Jacques Rogge, President of the International Olympic Committee.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The Singapore Games were then officially declared opened by S.R.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The Olympic Oath was taken on behalf of all athletes by Caroline Chew, on behalf of all judges by Syed Abdul Kadir, and on behalf of all coaches by David Lim Fong Jock.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Finally, a boat in the shape of a phoenix carried the Youth Olympic Flame across Marina Bay and was passed between six Singaporean youth athletes in a relay.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Sailor Darren Choy was the final torchbearer and lit the cauldron.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The 32-metre (105 ft) tall cauldron was designed by Dr.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Tsai Her-Mann, a fellow and resident inventor of the Singapore Science Centre.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Designed to look like a lighthouse, its distinctive feature was a swirling 8 m (26 ft) column of fire dubbed the "vortex flame" or "fire tornado" inside a tube with an opening at the top end.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Hot air that could reach 300 °C (572 °F) created around the flame rose, drawing cool air upwards from openings in the base of the tower.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Just below the glass-panelled portion of the tower, the cool air was driven through angled guide vanes, thus creating the spiralling movement travelling upwards at 20 m/s (66 ft/s).
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The cauldron, which had been patented in Singapore and the United States, consumed about 2 MW (2,700 hp) of fuel, less than half the amount used by conventional Olympic cauldrons.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Tsai said he hoped his design could be used for other Olympic events in future.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The cauldron was secretly tested at 4:00 am during the two months leading up to the opening ceremony.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The Games featured 26 sports with a total of 31 disciplines and 201 events.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Within the 201 events, there were 8 mixed team events (Mixed-NOCs), 4 mixed team events (NOCs), 1 open event (Equestrian), 106 men's events, and 82 women's events.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] These included two disciplines under the IOC classification of aquatics (diving and swimming), and three under gymnastics (artistic, rhythmic and trampoline).
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Each sport in the Games was represented by a pictogram inspired by the official "Spirit of Youth" emblem consisting of a red flame, a blue star and a green crescent, which was depicted participating in each of the 26 sports of the Youth Olympic Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The sport pictograms had a distinctive, contemporary graphic style that was intended to make them a highly recognisable feature of the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] About 3,600 athletes, aged 14 to 18, participated in the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] All 205 National Olympic Committees (NOCs) were represented, except Kuwait, which was suspended in January 2010 due to alleged government interference; however, three Kuwaiti athletes competed under the Olympic flag.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] A unique feature of the YOG was the creation of the mixed-NOCs team event.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] To foster friendship among participants, teams were formed by athletes from different countries to compete on an intercontinental basis.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Mixed-NOC sports included equestrian-jumping, fencing, judo, modern pentathlon, and triathlon.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] There were eight events which composed entirely of mixed-NOCs teams, and as such all 25 medals in these events, including two bronzes in judo, were swept by mixed-NOCs teams.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The first gold medal of the Games was awarded to 18-year-old Japanese triathlete Yuka Sato, who won the girls' event on 15 August.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Host nation Singapore's first medal was a bronze in taekwondo for Daryl Tan on 16 August.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The first gold medal for a mixed-NOC event was awarded to team Europe 1, consisting of Yana Egoryan of Russia and Italians Marco Fichera Marco, Camilla Mancini, Leonardo Affede, Alberta Santuccio Alberta and Eduardo Luperi, which won the team competition in fencing.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The IOC set a vision for the YOG to be an event comprising a balance of sports, culture and education.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The objective of the Culture and Education Programme (CEP) that athletes participated in was to educate, engage and influence the athletes to develop true sportsmanship and to live by the Olympic values of excellence, respect and friendship, while having fun at the same time.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] To promote cultural education among the participating youths, the YOG programme incorporated live youth performances, art installations and festivals revolving around the Olympics spirit and cultural diversity.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Singapore's Youth Olympic Games Learning Centre is located at the SYOGOC headquarters along Kay Siang Road.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] It was officially opened by the SNOC President Teo Chee Hean and former pole vaulting champion Sergei Bubka on 30 October 2008.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The two-storey, 600-square-metre (6,500 sq ft) facility was open to the public for free allow visitors to discover and experience the spirit of the Olympics and trace Singapore's Games journey from winning the bid to host the first YOG in 2010.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] It featured several sections aimed at educating the public about different sports, as well as the history of Olympic records and the events lined up for the YOG.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The public could also try their hand at table tennis, fencing and basketball at interactive sections.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] It subsequently closed for renovations from 18 August till the end of 2010.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The closing ceremony of the Games was held on 26 August at The Float@Marina Bay.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The show began proper at 8pm Singapore time with youths, cheerleaders and the YOG mascots Lyo and Merly dancing to a medley of "Fame" and "Fight for This Love".
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Following the arrival of IOC President Jacques Rogge and Prime Minister of Singapore Lee Hsien Loong, 12-year-old Nathania Ong led the choir and the audience in singing the national anthem of Singapore.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] In the next segment "Blazing the Trail", 5 young singers performed an upbeat song while students dressed to resemble the "Spirit of Youth", the Singapore 2010 emblem, performed a mass display item.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Following the item, the athletes and the flags representing all competing nations made their way onto the floating platform.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] A short clip showing the highlights of the games was then shown on the LED screens on the stage, accompanied by singer Heleyana-Ann Lachica Fernandez and a trio of musicians performing "A New Story".
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The Protocol segment followed the performances.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] A tribute was made to the 20,000 volunteers who participated in the Games, with Singapore swimmer Rainer Ng making a short speech thanking the volunteers and eight other athletes presenting bouquets to eight representative volunteers.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] This was then followed by speeches from Ng Ser Miang, Chairman of the Singapore Youth Olympic Games Organising Committee, and Jacques Rogge, IOC President, with Mr.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Rogge officially declaring the Games closed in accordance with tradition.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The Olympic flag was then lowered with the singing of the Olympic Anthem.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] In the handover ceremony, the Olympic flag was handed over from Teo Ser Luck, acting as the Mayor of Singapore, through Jacques Rogge, to Ji Jianye, Mayor of Nanjing, China, the host city of the 2014 Summer Youth Olympics.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The national anthem of China was then played with the raising of China's flag, and a short video presentation showcasing Nanjing followed.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The Youth Olympic Flame was then finally extinguished to the sounds of a flugelhorn.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] A Celebration Concert marked the end of the show with songs and performances from local artistes.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Although the SYOGOC did not keep an official medal tally, news outlets, such as xinmsn, kept unofficial medal tables, where medals won by mixed-NOCs teams are credited to the NOCs that the athletes belong to.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The following table lists the top ten ranked NOCs and the host nation.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] See 2010 Summer Youth Olympics medal table for more details and a full table with medals won by mixed-NOCs teams counted separately.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The Games organisers used online media to market the event, including Friendster, Facebook, Twitter, WordPress and the official Youth.sg 2010 discussion forum.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Contracts were signed with 166 broadcasters to provide worldwide television broadcasts for the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] These include China Central Television, which telecast the opening ceremony live and has been screening nine hours of coverage each day on its CCTV-5 sports channel, and the Universal Sports television network in the United States.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] In Canada, the games were broadcast by Canada's Olympic Broadcast Media Consortium, a joint venture between CTVglobemedia and Rogers Media.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Coverage of those games was limited to a one-hour daily highlights package on Sportsnet and TSN2 (rebroadcast several weeks later on TSN).
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The consortium did not, however, own rights to the 2012 Winter Youth Olympics in Innsbruck.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The SYOGOC launched an international emblem design competition on 29 July 2008 through 29 August 2008 through its official website, requiring that the emblem incorporate the three themes of the Singapore identity, the Olympic ideals, and a youthful spirit.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The emblem competition for the Games attracted 1,500 participants, and the winning design entitled "Spirit of Youth" was unveiled on 10 January 2010.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] A contest to choose the official medal design for the first Youth Olympics was launched by the IOC in 2009.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] From November to December almost a hundred entries from 34 countries were received.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The mascots of the Games were Lyo and Merly, a fire-themed lion and a water-themed female merlion respectively.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The official theme song of the Games was "Everyone".
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] It was performed by five singers representing six continents of the world, namely, Jody Williams (Africa), Sean Kingston (Americas), Tabitha Nauser (Asia), Steve Appleton (Europe) and Jessica Mauboy (Oceania).
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The executive producer of the song was local music producer Ken Lim.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The initial budget of 108 million SGD was exceeded over three times amounting to more than 300 million SGD.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The latter was denied by organisers, SYOGOC Chairman Ng Ser Miang saying: "[J]ust look at the faces of the children that are there, the sparkle in their eyes and the smiles on their faces.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Members of the public commented that although some events were sold out, there appeared to be many unoccupied seats at venues, and claimed that this was because the Ministry of Education (MOE) made a block purchase of 87,000 passes to be given to schools.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] However, students usually did not stay for the full duration of sessions, which can be up to seven hours long.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The MOE denied that students were to blame, stating that more than 95% of students allocated tickets had attended events, and that some schools had asked to purchase additional tickets due to overwhelming demand.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The SYOGOC announced that once sessions had begun, unoccupied seats would be resold to people who turned up in person at venues.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] To enable venue managers to gauge the number of seats available for resale, teachers escorting students to events were instructed to inform venue managers if they intended to leave before sessions ended and the number of seats occupied by students.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] On 20 August, the organisers reported that tickets were sold out for all 26 sports except girls' football.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Controversy also arose from the YOG attendance policy in Kuo Chuan Presbyterian Primary School, a local primary school.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The school stated that a S$5 refundable deposit was required from students who attend the YOG events on a non-school day.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] The principal, Clifford Chua, said that it was to "ensure that our children learn the value of responsibility and not take this rare opportunity for granted, by wasting the ticket and depriving others of the chance".
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Also, the deposit was returned even if the child did not attend the event.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] However, the move garnered mixed reactions from parents, who either supported the idea or felt it was not the right way to do things.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Some other schools such as Nanyang Girls High School, Bukit View Primary School and Park View Primary School gave free tickets to their students while Anglo-Chinese School (Primary) encouraged co-pay of $1 to $2 by the students to teach them to treasure their tickets.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] On 16 August 2010, Iranian officials withdrew Mohammed Soleimani from the men's under-48-kilogram category taekwondo final against Israel's Gili Haimovitz, citing an ankle injury.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] According to the officials, Soleimani had first hurt his ankle at the World Junior Championships in Mexico earlier in the year, and the injury had flared up again during his semifinal contest against the US's Gregory English.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Soleimani was sent to hospital for an X-ray, and his ankle was put into a cast.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Haimovitz was awarded the gold medal by default at a victory ceremony at the Suntec International Convention Centre from which Soleimani, the silver medallist, was absent.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Interviewed later on, Soleimani said he was "very sad" to have missed the bout as he was "sure [he] was going to get the gold medal".
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Israel's chef-de-mission Daniel Oren claimed that the pullout had been politically motivated.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] He said: "It's not the first time this has happened at the Olympics.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] To be honest, once our boy got into the final, we knew that this is going to happen.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] I spoke to our boy after the final and he, of course, was disappointed that he did not have a chance to win his gold through an actual fight.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] He must have trained hard to get to this stage and was not given a chance to fight.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] We are dealing with sports here, youth sports, in fact.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] It's a pity that politics got involved." However, IOC spokesman Mark Adams said: "As far as the IOC is concerned, there is no sinister intent here.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] What we know factually is that the athlete injured his ankle and was sent to the hospital for an X-ray.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Tests revealed he did not suffer anything broken, and he is all right now.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] For us, that's the end of the story." Previously, Iran has stated that since its existing government does not recognize Israel as a state, its policy is to withdraw from competing against the country.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Arturo Garcia, chairman of the Coaches Association of Santa Cruz in Bolivia, told the Bolivian newspaper *La Razón* he had proof that at least five players in the Bolivian boys' football team had been over the age limit of 15 years.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Bolivia beat Haiti 5–0 to take the gold medal in the finals of the boys' football tournament on 25 August 2010.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Bolivian Deputy Sports Minister Miguel Angel Rimba ordered an investigation into the claim.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Montenegro coach Sava Kovačević, whose team was knocked out by Bolivia in the semifinals, said that Montenegro would ask football governing body FIFA to look into the matter.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] However, FIFA announced they would not be doing so as complaints concerning the eligibility of players should have been submitted in writing to FIFA's headquarters in Singapore at the Youth Olympic Games no later than five days before the first match, that is, by 8 August.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] FIFA also said that its staff had met all footballers individually at the Olympic Village and had checked their passports against their dates of birth provided by their respective National Olympic Committees.
[src:3x3-basketball/2010-summer-youth-olympics] Two wrestlers, Greco-Roman 50 kg silver medallist Nurbek Hakkulov of Uzbekistan and 63 kg freestyle wrestler Johnny Pilay of Ecuador, were disqualified on 15 October after testing positive for the banned diuretic furosemide.
[src:3x3-basketball/2014-fiba-europe-3x3-championships] The **2014 FIBA Europe 3x3 Championships**, hosted at the University Square in Bucharest, Romania, was the inaugural European 3x3 basketball event that featured separate competitions for men's and women's national teams.
[src:3x3-basketball/2014-fiba-europe-3x3-championships] The tournament was held from 5 to 7 September 2014.
[src:3x3-basketball/2014-fiba-europe-3x3-championships] In the final of the men's tournament, host Romania beat Slovenia to win their first European championship title.
[src:3x3-basketball/2014-fiba-europe-3x3-championships] In the final of the women's tournament, Russia also beat Slovenia to win their first European championship title.
[src:3x3-basketball/2014-fiba-europe-3x3-championships] Slovenia finished in second place in both the men's and women's tournaments.
[src:3x3-basketball/2014-fiba-europe-3x3-championships] The qualification events took place in the summer of 2014.
[src:3x3-basketball/2014-fiba-europe-3x3-championships] A total of 15 teams of each gender (excluding the hosts Romania) qualified for the final tournament.
[src:3x3-basketball/2014-fiba-europe-3x3-championships] Was held in Zánka, Hungary, 12–13 July 2014.
[src:3x3-basketball/2014-fiba-europe-3x3-championships] Was held in Amsterdam, Netherlands, 19–20 July 2014.
[src:3x3-basketball/2014-fiba-europe-3x3-championships] Top four, excluding hosts Romania, will qualify.
[src:3x3-basketball/2014-fiba-europe-3x3-championships] Was held in Riga, Latvia, 2–3 August 2014.
[src:3x3-basketball/2014-fiba-europe-3x3-championships] Top five, excluding hosts Romania, will qualify.
[src:3x3-basketball/2014-fiba-europe-3x3-championships] Groups were announced on 27 August 2014.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The **2020 Summer Olympics**, officially the **Games of the XXXII Olympiad** and officially branded as **Tokyo 2020**, were an international multi-sport event held from July 23 to August 8, 2021, in Tokyo, Japan, with some of the preliminary sporting events beginning on July 21, 2021.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Tokyo was selected as the host city during the 125th IOC Session in Buenos Aires, Argentina, on September 7, 2013.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Originally scheduled to take place from July 24 to August 9, 2020, the Tokyo Games were postponed until 2021 on March 24, 2020 as a result of the global COVID-19 pandemic, the first such postponement in the history of the Olympic Games (some previous editions had been cancelled but not rescheduled).
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] However, the **Tokyo 2020** branding was retained for marketing purposes.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The events were largely held behind closed doors with no public spectators permitted due to the declaration of a state of emergency in the Greater Tokyo Area in response to the pandemic, the only Olympic Games to be held without official spectators.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] As a consequence of the postponement and the additional challenges caused by the pandemic, the 2020 Games were the most costly ever, with a total expenditure of over $20 billion.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The 2020 Games were the fourth Olympics to be held in Japan, following the 1964 Summer Olympics (Tokyo), the 1972 Winter Olympics (Sapporo), and the 1998 Winter Olympics (Nagano).
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Tokyo became the first city in Asia to hold the Summer Olympic Games twice.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The 2020 Games were the second of three consecutive Olympics to be held in East Asia, following the 2018 Winter Olympics in Pyeongchang, South Korea, and preceding the 2022 Winter Olympics in Beijing, China.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Because of the one-year postponement, Tokyo 2020 is the only Olympic Games to have taken place in an odd-numbered year.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] New events were introduced in existing sports, including 3x3 basketball, freestyle BMX, and mixed-gender team events in a number of existing sports, as well as the return of madison cycling for men and an introduction of the same event for women.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] New IOC policies allowed the host city's organizing committee to add new sports to the Olympic program for just one Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The disciplines added by the Japanese Olympic Committee were baseball and softball, karate, sport climbing, surfing, and skateboarding; the last four of these were making their Olympic debuts, and the last three have remained on the Olympic program.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The United States topped the medal table both by gold (39) and total medals (113), with China finishing second (38 and 89, respectively).
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Host nation Japan finished third, setting a record for the most gold and overall medals won by their delegation at an Olympic Games with 27 and 58, respectively.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Great Britain finished fourth, with 22 gold and 64 total medals.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The Russian delegation, competing as the ROC, finished fifth with 20 gold medals and third in the overall medal count, with 71 medals.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Bermuda, the Philippines, and Qatar won their first-ever Olympic gold medals.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Burkina Faso, San Marino, and Turkmenistan also won their first-ever Olympic medals.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The three candidate cities were Tokyo, Istanbul, and Madrid.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The applicant cities of Baku and Doha were not promoted to candidate status.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The International Olympic Committee (IOC) voted to select the host city of the 2020 Summer Olympics on September 7, 2013, at the 125th IOC Session in Buenos Aires, Argentina, using an exhaustive ballot system.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] None of the candidate cities won more than 50% of the votes in the first round; Madrid and Istanbul were tied for second place, so a runoff vote was held to determine which of the two cities would be eliminated.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The final vote was a head-to-head contest between Tokyo and Istanbul.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Tokyo was selected by 60 votes to 36, gaining at least the 49 votes required for a majority.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In January 2020, concerns were raised about the potential impact of the COVID-19 pandemic on athletes and visitors to the Summer Olympic Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Tokyo organizers and the International Olympic Committee insisted they were monitoring the spread of the disease to minimize its effects on preparations for the Olympics.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The IOC stated that in 2020, their Japanese partners and Prime Minister Shinzo Abe "made it very clear that Japan could not manage a postponement beyond next summer [2021] at the latest".
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Unlike the case for Zika virus during the 2016 Summer Olympics in Rio de Janeiro, SARS-CoV-2 can be transmitted directly between humans, posing tougher challenges for the organizers to counteract the infectious disease and host a safe and secure event.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Also unlike the case for H1N1 "swine flu" during the 2010 Winter Olympics in Vancouver, COVID-19 has a higher fatality rate, and there was no effective vaccine until December 2020.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In a February 2020 interview, Conservative London mayoral candidate Shaun Bailey argued that London would be able to host the Olympic Games at the former 2012 Olympic venues should the Games need to be moved because of the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Tokyo Governor Yuriko Koike criticized Bailey's comment as inappropriate.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In early 2021, officials in the US state of Florida offered to host the delayed Games in their state, while John Coates, the IOC vice president in charge of the Tokyo Olympics, said the Games would open even if the city and other parts of Japan were under a state of emergency because of COVID-19.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Estimates by the National Institute of Infectious Diseases and Kyoto University predicted that states of emergency might be required during the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The reports published at the Ministry of Health experts' panel also showed new patients increasing to 10,000 if the Games were to allow spectators.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Concerns about the pandemic began to affect qualifying events in early 2020.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Some that were due to take place in February were moved to alternative locations to address concerns about traveling to the affected areas, particularly China.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] For example, the women's basketball qualification was played in Belgrade, Serbia, instead of Foshan, China.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The Asia & Oceania boxing qualification tournament, which was originally planned to be held from February 3–14 in Wuhan, China (the location of the original outbreak of the COVID-19 pandemic), instead took place in Amman, Jordan, at the beginning of March.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The third round of the women's football qualification tournament was also affected, as the group matches formerly scheduled to be held in China were moved to Australia.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The European boxing qualification began on March 14, 2020 in London, United Kingdom, but was suspended after two days of competition before being rescheduled for April 2021.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] It eventually resumed in June 2021 but was moved to Paris, France, because of renewed concerns over travel to the UK.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Other qualifying events that were due to take place in March to June 2020 began to be postponed until later in the year and mid-2021 as part of a wider suspension of international sporting competitions in response to the pandemic.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] A multitude of Olympic sports were affected, including archery, baseball, cycling, handball, judo, rowing, sailing, volleyball, and water polo.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Mandatory doping tests were significantly restricted by the COVID-19 pandemic in early 2020.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] European anti-doping organizations raised concerns that blood and urine tests could not be performed and that mobilizing the necessary staff before the pandemic's end would pose health risks.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Despite the need for extensive testing ahead of the Games, the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) stated that public health and safety remained its top priority.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The China Anti-Doping Agency (CHINADA) temporarily suspended testing on February 3, 2020, with plans to resume phased testing later that month.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] By the end of March, anti-doping organizations in the US, France, Great Britain, and Germany had also reduced their testing activities.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] It was subsequently revealed that 23 Chinese swimmers had tested positive for the drug trimetazidine, but were permitted to compete, after CHINADA claimed they had ingested tiny amounts unawares from a kitchen.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Some, including Zhang Yufei, Wang Shun, and Qin Haiyang, went on to win medals.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The affair resulted in deep upset amongst the international athletic community.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The Tokyo Organizing Committee of the Olympic and Paralympic Games (TOCOG) released a statement on March 2, 2020, confirming that preparations for the upcoming Tokyo Olympics were "continuing as planned".
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On March 23, both Canada and Australia indicated that they would withdraw from the Games if they were not postponed by a year.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On the same day, Japanese prime minister Shinzo Abe stated he would support a proposed postponement, citing that ensuring athlete safety was "paramount", and veteran IOC member and former vice president Dick Pound said he expected the Games to be postponed.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On March 24, 2020, 122 days to go for the planned start, the IOC, TOCOG, and prime minister Abe released a joint statement announcing that the 2020 Summer Olympics and Paralympics would be rescheduled to a date "beyond 2020 but not later than summer 2021".
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] They stated that the Games could "stand as a beacon of hope to the world during these troubled times", and that the Olympic flame could become "the light at the end of the tunnel in which the world finds itself at present".
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Prime Minister Abe stated that IOC president Thomas Bach responded "with 100% agreement" to his proposal to delay the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] For continuity and marketing purposes, it was agreed that the Games would still be branded as Tokyo 2020 despite the change in schedule.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On March 30, 2020, the IOC and TOCOG announced that they had reached an agreement on the new dates for the 2020 Summer Olympics, which would begin with the opening ceremony on July 23, 2021 and end with the closing ceremony on August 8, 2021, still to be held in Tokyo.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The subsequent Winter Olympics in Beijing were scheduled to begin on February 4, 2022, less than six months later.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Shortly before the postponement was confirmed, the IOC and Tokyo 2020 organizers formed a task force named "Here We Go" with the remit to address any issues arising from postponing the Games, such as sponsorship and accommodation.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The organizers confirmed that all athletes who had already qualified for Tokyo 2020 prior to March 24, 2020 would keep their qualification slots.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Health experts expressed concern in April 2020 that the Games might have to be cancelled if the pandemic should persist.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In an interview, the then president of TOCOG and former Japanese prime minister, Yoshirō Mori, asserted that the Games would be "scrapped" if they could not go ahead in 2021.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On April 29, 2020, Prime Minister Abe stated that the Games "must be held in a way that shows the world has won its battle against the coronavirus pandemic".
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Thomas Bach acknowledged in an interview on May 20, 2020, that the job of reorganizing the Tokyo Games was "a mammoth task" and also admitted that the event would have to be cancelled altogether if it could not take place in the summer of 2021.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] However, both Mori and Bach expressed optimism about the Games going ahead.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On January 21, 2021, multiple sources reported that the Japanese government had "privately concluded" that the Games would have to be cancelled.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The government dismissed the claims, stating the reports were "categorically untrue".
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The new Japanese prime minister Yoshihide Suga confirmed on February 19 that the G7 had given unanimous support for the postponed Games to go ahead as scheduled.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Public support for the Games in Japan decreased significantly amid a 2021 surge in COVID-19 cases in the country.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Multiple organizations of medical professionals voiced oppositions to the Games, while an opinion poll in April 2021 saw 40% of participants support the cancellation of the Games and 33% support a second postponement.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In May 2021, 83% of those polled supported the cancellation or postponement of the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The Tokyo Medical Practitioners Association called for cancellation, stating that hospitals in Tokyo "have their hands full and have almost no spare capacity" in an open letter to the prime minister.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] At least nine out of 47 elected governors supported cancellation of the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Nearly 37% of Japanese companies surveyed supported cancellation of the Games, and 32% supported postponement.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Kenji Utsunomiya, who had previously run for Governor of Tokyo, collected more than 351,000 signatures on a petition calling for the organizers to "prioritize life" over the Olympics.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Japanese writers Jiro Akagawa and Fuminori Nakamura also called for the Games to be postponed or cancelled.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In July 2021, it was announced that all events in Tokyo were to be held behind closed doors with no spectators due to a new state of emergency.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] A poll by the *Asahi Shimbun* found that 55% of those surveyed supported cancellation of the Olympics, and 68% felt that organizers would not be able to suitably control COVID-19 at the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Had the Games been cancelled, it would have been the first time since World War II that an Olympic event had been called off and the first Games to be scrapped due to circumstances unrelated to war.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The Tokyo Games were protected through the commercial insurance marketplace Lloyd's of London, by global reinsurers Munich Re and Swiss Re.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The IOC takes out around $800 million of insurance for each Summer Olympics, with the total amount of loss insured for the 2020 Games likely to be more than $2 billion.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The disruption caused by postponing the Games was covered by the insurance policy, with those likely to make claims for their financial losses including local organizers, sponsors, hospitality firms, and travel providers.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Holders of tickets purchased from overseas prior to postponement were entitled to refunds for both Olympic and Paralympic ticket purchases, except for the costs of cancelled hotel bookings.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Although about 600,000 Olympic tickets and 300,000 Paralympic tickets were eligible to be refunded, organizers said they would not release the total costs of the refunds.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The local organizers are responsible for ticket sales and use them to defray the costs of holding the Games; ticket sales were expected to bring in approximately US$800 million, but actual sales were close to zero.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In June 2022, the Tokyo Organizing Committee revealed in the final budget report for the Tokyo Olympics and Paralympics that the cost for the Olympic Games was 640.4 billion yen (US$5.8 billion), which was higher than the cost for the Rio 2016.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The total, final cost of the delayed Games was 1.4 trillion yen (US$13 billion).
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Prior to the Tokyo Olympics being held, many Japanese people were negative about hosting the event, but their attitudes had become more positive toward the end of the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] However, 64% answered it was good that the Tokyo Games had gone ahead, while 28% answered that they wished the event had not been held.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Of the respondents, 61% were glad the event had been held without spectators, and only 12% said that spectators should have been allowed.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On July 29, less than a week into the Games, journalist Masaki Kubota reported his analysis of the Japanese people's perspective on the Olympics, which he believed was greatly influenced by the change in the way the Japanese news media reported on the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Once the Tokyo Olympics were underway, followed by the Tokyo Paralympics, there was a sharp increase in COVID-19 cases in Japan, especially those caused by the Delta variant.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On July 26, there were 60,157 cases detected in Japan, breaking the record of 44,961 cases recorded on May 10.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On August 9, one day after the Olympics had ended, daily cases in Japan reached 100,000 for the first time, and new cases continued to increase until the peak on August 23, when 156,931 cases were recorded.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The Tokyo Organizing Committee was originally headed by former Japanese prime minister Yoshirō Mori, but he resigned in February 2021 due to backlash from sexist comments about women in meetings.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Seiko Hashimoto was chosen to succeed him.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Tamayo Marukawa, Minister for the Tokyo Olympic and Paralympic Games, was responsible for overseeing the preparations on behalf of the Japanese government.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The Tokyo Metropolitan Government set aside a fund of ¥400 billion (more than US$3.67 billion) to cover the cost of hosting the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The Japanese government was considering easing airspace restrictions to allow an increased slot capacity at both Haneda and Narita airports.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] A new railway line was planned to link both airports through an expansion of Tokyo Station, cutting travel time from Tokyo Station to Haneda from 30 to 18 minutes, and from Tokyo Station to Narita from 55 to 36 minutes; funded primarily by private investors, the line would cost ¥400 billion.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The East Japan Railway Company (JR East) was also planning a new route near Tamachi to Haneda Airport.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] There were plans to fund the accelerated completion of the Central Circular Route, Tokyo Gaikan Expressway, and Ken-Ō Expressway, and the refurbishment of other major expressways in the area.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In April 2018, the Tokyo Organizing Committee signed a partnership with the International Labour Organization to ensure decent work in the preparation of and during the 2020 Olympic Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In June 2020, the chief executive of the Organizing Committee, Toshirō Mutō, stated that the committee was exploring options for streamlining the Games to achieve cost savings.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On September 25, the IOC and Tokyo Organizing Committee agreed to a suite of measures to simplify the Games' logistics, including a cut to non-athlete staff, use of online meetings, and streamlined transport, among others.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The committee also outlined areas it would be exploring to maintain the health and safety of all participants.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In February 2012, it was announced that Tokyo's former National Stadium, the central venue for the 1964 Summer Olympics, would undergo a ¥100 billion renovation for the 2019 Rugby World Cup and the 2020 Summer Olympics.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In November 2012, the Japan Sport Council announced it was taking bids for proposed stadium designs.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Of the 46 finalists, Zaha Hadid Architects was awarded the project, which would replace the old stadium with a new 80,000-seat stadium.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] There was criticism of Hadid's design—which was compared to a bicycle helmet and regarded as clashing with the surrounding Meiji Shrine—and widespread disapproval of the costs, even with attempts to revise and "optimize" the design.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In June 2015, the government announced plans to reduce the new stadium's permanent capacity to 65,000 in its athletics configuration (although with the option to add up to 15,000 temporary seats for football) as a further cost-saving measure.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The original plan to build a retractable roof was also abandoned.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] At the end of 2015, in response to public opposition to the increasing costs of the new stadium (which had reached ¥252 billion), the government chose to reject Hadid's design entirely and selected a new design by Japanese architect Kengo Kuma.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Inspired by traditional temples and with a lower profile, Kuma's design had a budget of ¥149 billion.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The changes meant the new stadium could not be completed in time for the 2019 Rugby World Cup as originally intended.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The National Stadium, which was inaugurated on December 21, 2019, was named the Olympic Stadium for the duration of the Tokyo Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In October 2018, the Board of Audit issued a report stating that the total cost of the Olympic venues could exceed US$25 billion.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Of the 33 competition venues in Tokyo, 28 were within 8 kilometers (5 miles) of the Olympic Village, with eleven new venues to be constructed.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On October 16, 2019, the IOC announced plans to re-locate the marathon and racewalking events to Sapporo for heat concerns.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The plans were made official on November 1, 2019, after Tokyo Governor Yuriko Koike accepted the IOC's decision, despite her belief that the events should have remained in Tokyo.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In general, as urban studies scholar Faure notes, "The Tokyo 2020–2021 Games had a relatively moderate impact on the city, compared to previous cases such as Rio and Sochi, or cases in which a major Olympic park was built in Barcelona in 1992, and in Beijing in 2008.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The transport infrastructure has been marginally improved by facilitating access for people with mobility constraints and improving signage in other languages.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Haneda Airport has been expanded, and a hydrogen-powered bus rapid transit system has been introduced.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Several sports and event facilities were built, including the new Olympic Stadium.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In December 2018, the Japanese government chose to ban drones from flying over venues being used for the Olympic and Paralympic Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] A similar ban was also imposed for the 2019 Rugby World Cup, which Japan also hosted.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In January 2020, counterterrorism drills began in different parts where the Games would take place, after intelligence data showed that terrorist groups could have carried out an attack to seek worldwide attention.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In July 2021, prior to the start of the Games, the Japan Coast Guard conducted counterterrorism drills in the Tokyo Bay.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The drill consisted of two inflatable boats trying to stop a suspicious ship from getting to shore.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Applications for volunteering at the 2020 Olympic and Paralympic Games were accepted beginning on September 26, 2018.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] By January 18, 2019, a total of 204,680 applications had been received by the Tokyo Organizing Committee.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Interviews to select the requisite number of volunteers began in February 2019, with training scheduled to take place in October 2019.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Volunteers at the venues were to be known as "Field Cast", and volunteers in the city were to be known as "City Cast".
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] These names were chosen from a shortlist of four from an original 150 pairs of names; the other three shortlisted names were "Shining Blue" and "Shining Blue Tokyo", "Games Anchor" and "City Anchor", and "Games Force" and "City Force".
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The names were chosen by people who had applied to be volunteers at the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] As of early June 2021, approximately 10,000 out of the 80,000 registered volunteers resigned from the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Media attributed the rise in pandemic cases as the reason for massive quitting.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] More volunteer assignments were expected to be cancelled due to the spectator ban.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In February 2017, the Tokyo Organizing Committee announced an electronics recycling program in partnership with Japan Environmental Sanitation Center and NTT Docomo, soliciting donations of electronics, such as mobile phones, to be reclaimed as materials for the medals.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Aiming to collect eight tonnes of metals to produce the medals for the Olympic and Paralympic Games, collection boxes were deployed at public locations and NTT Docomo retail shops in April 2017.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] A design competition for the medals was launched in December of that year.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The collection of bronze was completed in November 2018, with the remainder estimated to have been completed by March 2019.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On July 24, 2019 (one year ahead of the originally scheduled opening ceremony), the designs of the medals were unveiled.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The medals for the Olympic and Paralympic Games were designed by Junichi Kawanishi following a nationwide competition.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] A new feature shared with the Paralympic medals is that the ribbons contain one, two, or three silicone convex lines to distinguish gold, silver, and bronze medals, respectively.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The 2020 Summer Olympics podiums were made from plastic waste donated by the Japanese population.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Artist Asao Tokolo was tasked with their design, which was produced using 3D printing technology with 400,000 laundry detergent bottles (24.5 tons) collected from stores and schools across the country for over nine months.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Each podium was constructed from a series of small, 3D-printed cube-shaped modules that were connected to form the three traditional pedestals.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] For the Paralympic Games, they could be transformed into a flat, accessible platform.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The modules were rendered in the same shade of blue as the Tokyo 2020’s logo, and the Olympic rings in front of the podiums were made from recycled aluminum, originally used to form temporary housing for those impacted by the major earthquake in eastern Japan in 2011.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The slogan of the 2020 Summer Olympics torch relay was "Hope Lights Our Way".
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] As determined by a 2009 IOC ruling that banned international torch relays for any future Olympic Games, the 2020 Summer Olympics torch was scheduled to only visit two countries: Greece and host nation Japan.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The first phase of the relay began on March 12, 2020, with the traditional flame lighting ceremony at the Temple of Hera in Olympia, Greece.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The torch then travelled to Athens, where the Greek leg of the relay culminated in a handover ceremony at the Panathenaic Stadium on March 19, during which the torch was transferred to the Japanese contingent.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The flame was placed inside a special lantern and transported from Athens International Airport on a chartered flight to Higashimatsushima in Japan.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The torch was then expected to begin the second phase of its journey on March 20, as it traveled for one week around the three most affected areas of the 2011 Tōhoku earthquake and tsunami—Miyagi, Iwate and Fukushima—where it would go on display under the heading "Flame of Recovery".
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] After leaving Naraha on March 26, the torch would commence its main relay around Japan, incorporating all 47 prefectural capitals.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] After the decision to postpone the Games, the torch was placed again in a special lantern on display in the city of Fukushima for a month.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Then, the lantern was transferred to the Tokyo prefecture, where it was kept safe until the restart of the relay in 2021.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On August 20, 2020, it was announced that the torch relay would begin again in Naraha, Fukushima on March 25, 2021, nearly a year later than originally planned.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The final course of the relay was altered due to concerns regarding public health concerns about gatherings along the route (e.g., the Miyakojima leg was canceled), and the relay was held without spectators due to states of emergency in some regions (e.g., Matsuyama, Hiroshima, Hyōgo, and Okayama).
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The relay ended at Tokyo's National Stadium (Olympic Stadium) on July 23, with tennis player Naomi Osaka lighting the Olympic cauldron at the finale of the opening ceremony.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Participants would be asked to use Japan's COCOA Exposure Notification app and would be tested at least every four days.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Athletes who tested positive would be unable to compete and could be quarantined at a government facility (although leeway would be given in the event of false positives).
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Close contacts would also need to test negative to be cleared for competition.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Athletes would be discouraged from "excessive" celebrations because the actions could spread infected droplets.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The playbooks were criticized in a paper published by *The New England Journal of Medicine* in May 2021, for lacking "scientifically rigorous risk assessment" and failing to "distinguish the various levels of risk faced by athletes".
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The playbook stated that athletes were required to arrive up to five days prior to the start of the competition and to leave within 48 hours of being eliminated from their sport or the conclusion of the competitions.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The IOC recommended the vaccination of athletes against COVID-19 if vaccines were available to them, but this was not a prerequisite for participation and the IOC advised against athletes "jumping the queue" to obtain priority over essential populations.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On May 6, 2021, Pfizer announced it would donate doses of its vaccine to NOCs competing in Tokyo.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Approximately 93,000 athletes and officials were exempt from the quarantine rules upon arriving in Japan, provided they remained in areas separated from the local population.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] With around 300,000 local staff and volunteers entering and exiting these bubbles, and 20,000 vaccine doses allocated for this group, this led to concerns of COVID-19 spreading both during the Games and when teams returned to their countries.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Due to international travel restrictions, the organizing committee announced in March 2021 that no international guests (including spectators, and friends and family members of the athletes) would be allowed to attend the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] As per existing guidance for spectator sports in Japan, spectators would be asked to refrain from cheering or shouting.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On June 19, 2021, Governor Koike announced that plans for public viewing events for the Games had been scrapped, in order to use the planned venues (such as Yoyogi Park) as mass vaccination sites instead.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On June 21, it was announced that all venues would be capped at a maximum of 10,000 ticketed spectators or 50% capacity, whichever was lower.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On July 2, 2021, the new TOCOG president Seiko Hashimoto warned that there was still a possibility of the Games being held behind closed doors because of rising COVID-19 cases in the country.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Japan's slow vaccination rate was of particular concern.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] A simulation run by the University of Tokyo in May 2021 projected that a new wave of infections could peak in mid-October if the Games went on after the existing state of emergency in Tokyo had expired.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The announcement stated that spectators would still be allowed at events being held outside of Tokyo, subject to the approval by local health authorities and the aforementioned 50%/10,000-spectator limit.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The prefectures of Fukushima, Hokkaido, and Ibaraki announced they would prohibit spectators at events held in the areas.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The opening ceremony was expected to be limited to fewer than 1,000 VIP guests, including IOC representatives and dignitaries, while some events did allow members of other competing delegations to occupy spectator seats as well.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] School students were invited to watch football matches in Ibaraki.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On July 16, it was reported that Bach had asked Prime Minister Suga about the possibility of restrictions on spectators being eased later on if COVID-19 conditions were to improve in Tokyo.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] However, on August 2, Suga announced that all existing state of emergency declarations would be extended through August 31, and be extended to Chiba, Kanagawa, Saitama, and parts of Osaka.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The opening ceremony tickets were expected to range from ¥12,000 to ¥300,000, with a maximum price of ¥130,000 for the finals of the athletics track and field events.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The average ticket price was ¥7,700, with half the tickets being sold for up to ¥8,000.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] A symbolic ticket price of ¥2,020 was expected for families, groups resident in Japan, and in conjunction with a school program.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Tickets would be sold through 40,000 shops in Japan and by mail order to Japanese addresses through the internet.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] International guests, had they been allowed, would have needed to visit Japan during the sales period, or arrange to buy tickets through a third party such as a travel agent.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Tickets went on general sale in Japan in the autumn of 2019 and were expected to be sold globally from June 2020; however, this plan was suspended when the Games were postponed on March 24, 2020.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The Tokyo Organizing Committee confirmed that tickets already purchased would remain valid for the same sessions according to the new schedule and that refunds were also being offered.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On March 20, 2021, it was announced that due to COVID-19-related concerns, no international guests would be allowed to attend the 2020 Olympics or Paralympics.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] This included spectators, as well as the friends and family of athletes.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] All overseas ticketholders would be refunded.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Hashimoto cited uncertainties surrounding international travel restrictions, and goals to preserve the safety of all participants and spectators, and not place a burden on the health care system.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] It was ultimately announced in July that all local spectators were not allowed to attend any events held in Tokyo, Fukushima, and Hokkaido.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] This tournament would have differed significantly from the traditional bi-monthly *Honbasho* tournaments, and featured additional commentary in English and Japanese to help explain the customs and traditions of professional sumo, which are deeply rooted in the Shinto religion.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the original event program was cancelled in April 2020.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] A 10 m (33 feet)-tall puppet named Mocco—inspired by the writings of Naoki Matayoshi, and designed by illustrator Ryōji Arai based on ideas from Tōhoku youth—toured Iwate, Miyagi, and Fukushimai in support of tsunami recovery efforts.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] It was then transported to Shinjuku Gyo-en in Tokyo in mid-July for an exhibition prior to the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The opening ceremony was held on July 23, 2021, in the Olympic Stadium in Tokyo.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] It included the traditional Parade of Nations.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Emperor Naruhito formally opened the Games, and at the end of the torch relay, the Olympic cauldron was lit by Japanese tennis player Naomi Osaka.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] For the first time in the history of Olympic Games, it was decided that one male and one female from each country would take turns holding flags and serve as two of them.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] This was done by embodying the "Agenda 2020" set during President Bach's term.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] A moment of silence was observed in the opening ceremony for the victims of COVID-19 pandemic, the 2011 earthquake and tsunami, and the Munich massacre.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The event program for the Games was approved by the IOC executive board on June 9, 2017.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] IOC president Thomas Bach stated that their goal was to give the Games "youthful" and "urban" appeal, and to increase the number of female participants.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The Games featured 339 medal events in 33 different sports, encompassing a total of 51 disciplines.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Karate, sport climbing, surfing, and skateboarding made their Olympic debut, while baseball and softball also made a one-off return to the Summer Olympics for the first time since 2008.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] 15 new events within existing sports were also added, including 3×3 basketball, freestyle BMX, and the return of madison cycling, as well as nine new mixed events in several sports (table tennis, archery, judo, shooting (3), triathlon, 4 × 400 m relay running, and 4 × 100 m medley swimming).
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In the list below, the number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The new entrant would join golf and rugby sevens (which would both debut in 2016) as part of the program of 28 "core" sports.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Five sports were shortlisted for removal, including canoe, field hockey, modern pentathlon, taekwondo, and wrestling.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In the final round of voting by the executive board, eight members voted to remove wrestling from the Olympic program.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Field hockey and taekwondo tied in second with three votes each.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The 2013 decision to drop wrestling after Rio 2016 surprised many media outlets, given that the sport's role in the Olympics dates back to the ancient Olympic Games, and was included in the original program for the modern Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] *The New York Times* felt that the decision was based on the shortage of well-known talent and the absence of women's events in the sport.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Out of the shortlist from the IOC vote, wrestling was duly added to the shortlist of applicants for inclusion in the 2020 Games, alongside the seven new sports put forward for consideration.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On May 29, 2013, it was announced that three of the eight sports under consideration had made the final shortlist: baseball/softball, squash, and wrestling.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The other five sports were rejected at this point: karate, roller sports, sport climbing, wakeboarding, and wushu.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] At the 125th IOC Session on September 8, 2013, wrestling was chosen to be included in the Olympic program for 2020 and 2024.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Wrestling secured 49 votes, while baseball/softball and squash received 24 votes and 22 votes, respectively.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] With the adoption of the *Olympic Agenda 2020* in December 2014, the IOC shifted from a "sport-based" approach to the Olympic program to an "event-based" program—establishing that organizing committees may propose discretionary events to be included in the program to improve local interest.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] As a result of these changes, a shortlist of eight new proposed sports was unveiled on June 22, 2015, consisting of baseball/softball, bowling, karate, roller sports, sport climbing, squash, surfing, and wushu.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] On September 28, 2015, the Tokyo Organizing Committee submitted their shortlist of five proposed sports to the IOC: baseball/softball, karate, sport climbing, surfing, and skateboarding.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] These five new sports were approved on August 3, 2016, by the IOC during the 129th IOC Session in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, and were included in the sports program for 2020 only, bringing the total number of sports at the 2020 Olympics to 33.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] A total of 56 test events were scheduled to take place in the run-up to the 2020 Olympics and Paralympics.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Two of the events were held in late 2018, but the main test event schedule commenced in June 2019 and was originally due to be completed in May 2020 prior to the start of the Olympics.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] Several of the events were incorporated into pre-existing championships, but some had been newly created specifically to serve as Olympic test events for the 2020 Summer Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] In February 2019, it was announced that the test events would be branded under the banner "Ready, Steady, Tokyo".
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The Tokyo Organizing Committee was responsible for 22 of the test events, with the remaining events being arranged by national and international sports federations.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The first test event was World Sailing's World Cup Series, held at Enoshima in September 2018.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] The last scheduled event was the Tokyo Challenge Track Meet, which was originally due to take place at the Olympic Stadium on May 6, 2020.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p01] All test events originally scheduled to take place from March 12, 2020 onwards were postponed due to COVID-19, with the test event calendar to be reviewed during the preparations for the rescheduled Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The Republic of Macedonia has competed under the provisional name "Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia" in every Summer and Winter Games since its debut in 1996 because of the disputed status of its official name.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The naming disputes with Greece ended in 2018 with the signing of the Prespa agreement, and the country was officially renamed North Macedonia in February 2019.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The new name was immediately recognized by the IOC, although the Olympic Committee of North Macedonia (NMOC) was not officially adopted until February 2020.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The NMOC sent a delegation to the 2020 Winter Youth Olympics in January 2020, but the Tokyo Games were North Macedonia's first appearance at the Summer Olympics under its new name.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Since competing as Swaziland ten times at the Summer and Winter Olympics, Eswatini made its debut under that name after the renaming of the country by the king in 2018.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] As a result of the ban, WADA planned to allow individually cleared Russian athletes to take part in the 2020 Summer Olympics under a neutral banner, as instigated at the 2018 Winter Olympics, but they would be excluded from team sports.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The head of WADA's Compliance Review Committee, Jonathan Taylor, stated that the IOC would not be able to use the "Olympic Athletes from Russia" (OAR) designation as it did in 2018, emphasizing that neutral athletes could not be portrayed as representing a specific country.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Russia later filed an appeal to the Court of Arbitration for Sport (CAS) against WADA's decision.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] After reviewing the case on appeal, CAS ruled on December 17, 2020 that the penalty placed on Russia be reduced.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The ruling does allow for "Russia" to be displayed on the team uniform—although it should be no more visible than the "Neutral Athlete/Team" designation—as well as the use of the Russian flag's colors within the uniform's design.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] On February 19, 2021, it was announced that Russia would compete under the acronym "ROC" after the name of the Russian Olympic Committee, although the name of the committee itself in full could not be used to refer to the delegation.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The ROC team would be represented by the flag of the Russian Olympic Committee.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] On April 6, 2021, North Korea announced it would not participate in the 2020 Summer Olympics because of COVID-19 concerns.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] This marked North Korea's first absence from the Summer Olympics since 1988.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] In September, a month after the games concluded, the Olympic Committee of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea was banned from participation in the 2022 Winter Olympics, after they failed to participate in the Tokyo Olympics.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] On July 21, 2021, Guinea announced it would not be sending a delegation to the Tokyo Olympics, allegedly due to COVID-19 concerns, though media outlets suggested financial considerations may have been the real motivating factor.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Guinea later reversed the decision and confirmed it would be participating.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The following 206 teams qualified (including the 104 universality places guaranteed in athletics, under which all 206 NOCs may send competitors regardless of qualification).
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The 2020 schedule by session was approved by the IOC Executive Board on 18 July 2018, with the exception of swimming, diving, and artistic swimming.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] A more detailed schedule by event was released on 16 April 2019, still omitting a detailed schedule for the boxing events.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] A detailed boxing schedule was released in late 2019.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The original schedule was from 22 July to 9 August 2020.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] To postpone the Olympics until 2021, all events were delayed by 364 days (one day less than a full year to preserve the same days of the week), giving a new schedule of 21 July to 8 August 2021.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Naoki Satō composed the music for the medal ceremonies.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Satō chose not to employ any musical elements distinctive to Japan "because victory ceremonies are for athletes from around the world" and he wanted all medalists to "feel at ease" when taking their places on the podium, regardless of their nationality.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The bouquets presented to the athletes came from regions affected by the 2011 earthquake and tsunami.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The individual flowers were selected to represent the prefectures of Miyagi, Fukushima, Iwate, and Tokyo.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Per the historical precedent of swimming at the 2008 Summer Olympics in Beijing and figure skating at the 2018 Winter Olympics in Pyeongchang, swimming finals were held in the morning to allow live primetime broadcasts in the Americas.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] NBC paid substantial fees for rights to the Olympics, so the IOC has allowed NBC to influence event scheduling to maximize US television ratings when possible.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] On May 7, 2014, NBC agreed to a US$7.75 billion contract extension to air the Olympics through the 2032 Games, with the company being one of the IOC's major sources of revenue.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Japanese broadcasters were said to have criticized the decision, as swimming is one of the most popular Olympic events in the country.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The official emblems for the 2020 Olympics and Paralympics were unveiled on April 25, 2016; designed by Asao Tokolo, who won a nationwide design contest, it takes the form of a ring in an indigo-colored checkerboard pattern.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The design was meant to "express a refined elegance and sophistication that exemplifies Japan".
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The checkered design resembles a pattern called *ichimatsu moyo* that was popular during the Edo period in Japan from 1603 to 1867.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The designs replaced a previous emblem that had been scrapped after allegations it plagiarized the logo of the Théâtre de Liège in Belgium.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The Games' bid slogan was *Discover Tomorrow* (Japanese: 未来（あした）をつかもう, romanized: *Ashita o tsukamō*).
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] While *ashita* literally means "tomorrow", it is intentionally spelled as *mirai*, "future".
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The official slogan *United by Emotion* was unveiled on February 17, 2020.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The official mascot of the 2020 Summer Olympics was Miraitowa, a figure with blue-checkered *ichimatsu moyo* patterns inspired by the Games' official emblem.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Its fictional characteristics include the ability to teleport.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Created by Japanese artist Ryo Taniguchi, the mascots were selected from a competition process which took place in late 2017 and early 2018.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] A total of 2,042 candidate designs were submitted to the Tokyo Organizing Committee, which selected three pairs of unnamed mascot designs to present to Japanese elementary school students for the final decision.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The results of the selection were announced on February 28, 2018, and the mascots were named on July 22, 2018.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Miraitowa is named after the Japanese words for "future" and "eternity".
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The mascots were expected to help finance the Tokyo Games through merchandizing and licensing deals.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Alongside the main *Emblem blue*, five other colors were used in the branding of the 2020 Games: *Kurenai red*, *Ai blue*, *Sakura pink*, *Fuji purple*, and *Matsuba green*.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] These five traditional colors of Japan were used as sub-colors to create points of difference in the color variations.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Several controversial issues occurred during preparations for the Tokyo Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] There were allegations of bribery in the Japanese Olympic Committee's (JOC) bid and of plagiarism in the initial design for the Games' logo.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] On December 10, 2018, the French financial crimes office began an investigation of Tsunekazu Takeda, the president of the Japanese Olympic Committee, concerning a 2013 scheme to obtain votes from African IOC members in support of Tokyo as host for the 2020 Olympics over Istanbul or Madrid.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] In March 2020, a Japanese businessman admitted to giving gifts, including cameras and watches, to IOC officials to lobby for their support of Tokyo's bid to host the Olympic Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The official emblems of the Tokyo Olympics and Paralympics, designed by Kenjirō Sano, were unveiled in July 2015 but were withdrawn and replaced following plagiarism accusations.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The lawsuit by Olivier Debie, who claimed his logo design was copied, was later dropped, with the designer citing escalating legal costs.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Mass logging for construction of the Olympic venues received international criticism.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] In February 2018, the Olympics Organizing Committee admitted that 87% of plywood panels used to build the new national stadium was sourced from endangered rainforests.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Portions of the Games were scheduled for locations impacted by the 2011 Tōhoku earthquake and tsunami, and the subsequent Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The hosting of events in these locations was promoted as a means of furthering recovery in the regions, with the Games sometimes being promoted as the "Recovery Olympics".
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] However, the organization of events in these regions faced criticism; Fukushima is considered safe by the World Health Organization and the United Nations, although scientific studies on the safety of the area are still disputed.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Some Tōhoku residents questioned the decision to use the region as a host site, arguing that preparations for the Games slowed down recovery efforts, and that the region lost workers to projects associated with the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Use of the flag in international sporting events such as the Olympic Games is controversial because it was used for waging aggressive war against many countries in Pacific regions, including the attack on Pearl Harbor.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] According to the Associated Press, the IOC issued a statement in response to South Korea's request, saying, "sports stadiums should be free of any political demonstration.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] In February 2021, the TOCOG president Yoshirō Mori resigned, after facing both domestic and international criticisms over his sexist remarks.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The previous conduct of the new president, Seiko Hashimoto, had also drawn criticisms, leading her to comment "I regret it and think I should be careful" on one of the accusations.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The head creative director for the opening and closing ceremonies, Hiroshi Sasaki, resigned in March 2021, after making demeaning comments about Naomi Watanabe.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The composer for the opening ceremony, Keigo Oyamada, resigned days before the ceremony after growing criticism of his past bullying of people with apparent disabilities, such as Down syndrome.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] On July 16, a week before the opening ceremony, TOCOG announced their support of Oyamada as a composer and vowed not to change his selection for the ceremonies, but growing criticism forced him to announce his resignation on July 19.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Officials reported that by early June 2021, about 10,000 of the 80,000 registered volunteers had quit.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] "There's no doubt that one of the reasons is concern over coronavirus infections," the chief executive of the Organizing Committee said, also stating he did not believe this would impact the operation of the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] On July 23, hundreds of anti-Olympic protestors gathered outside the Japan National Stadium before the opening ceremony.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Security guards blocked reporters from leaving the stadium to interview protestors.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] In total, more than 60,000 police were mobilized for security during the Games, and police were regularly deployed to break up public displays of protest, including tackling protestors on their way to join the anti-Olympic protest in Sendagaya during the closing ceremony on September 5, 2021.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Writing for *The Conversation*, Olympic scholar MacIntosh Ross raised concerns about the relationship between the IOC and WHO, suggesting the organizations showed a lack of concern for the health of Japanese citizens and Olympians.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Still, the story that Japan—or at least the LDP—wanted to tell, of a newly reborn and 'normal' Japan (re-)entering the world stage remained untold.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] A number of controversies arose during the Games, most notably the attempted repatriation on August 1 of Belarusian sprinter Krystsina Tsimanouskaya, allegedly for her criticism of the national sports authorities and team management.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Refusing to return to Belarus, over fears for her safety, Tsimanouskaya sought assistance from the IOC and traveled to Warsaw, Poland, on August 4 after being granted a humanitarian visa by Tokyo's Polish Embassy.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Near the end of the Olympics, it was reported that Australian athletes had damaged the village rooms before departure, leaving a pool of vomit on the floor, damaged beds, and a hole in the wall.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Australian rugby Olympians also reportedly became drunk on the flight to Sydney, leaving vomit in the plane bathroom and receiving complaints from other passengers.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Team Australia chief Ian Chesterman played down the incidents, and said the Olympians would not be punished.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Algerian judoka Fethi Nourine and his coach Amar Benikhlef were suspended for 10 years by the International Judo Federation after Nourine refused to fight an Israeli athlete at the Olympics.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Nourine said his political support for the Palestinians in the Israeli–Palestinian conflict made it impossible for him to compete against Israeli athletes.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Sudan's Mohamed Abdalarasool also withdrew from the competition to avoid the Israeli athlete.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] After the Olympics concluded, New Zealand diving judge Lisa Wright revealed that during the diving events, Zhou Jihong, Vice President of FINA from China, allegedly launched a verbal tirade at Wright at the conclusion of the men's 10 m platform final.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Wright alleged that Zhou verbally abused her for underscoring Chinese divers.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Diving New Zealand subsequently complained about the incident to FINA's Ethics Panel.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] As a result, Zhou was ordered by a FINA Ethics Panel decision to write a letter of apology to Wright.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] A recommendation was also made by the Ethics Panel to disestablish Zhou's position as Diving Bureau Liaison for FINA.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The FINA Ethics Panel stated that the incident during the men's platform final was "unfortunate" and led to a "misunderstanding mixed with misjudgement" between Wright and Zhou.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Latimer claimed that Zhou's behavior was tarnishing the reputation of international diving and that she was acting in the interests of China rather than international diving as a whole.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Subsequent to Latimer's complaint, video evidence emerged online showing Zhou coaching Chinese divers during competition sessions at the Olympics, a behavior considered unethical given her supposedly neutral role as a FINA Vice President and Diving Bureau Liaison.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] The Olympic Games Tokyo 2020 reached a global broadcast audience of 3.05 billion people, according to independent research conducted on behalf of the International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Sony and Panasonic partnered with NHK to develop broadcasting standards for 8K resolution television, with a goal to release 8K television sets in time for the 2020 Summer Olympics.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] In early 2019, Italian broadcaster RAI announced its intention to deploy 8K broadcasting for the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] NHK broadcast the opening and closing ceremonies, and coverage of selected events in 8K.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Telecom company NTT Docomo signed a deal with Finland's Nokia to provide 5G-ready baseband networks in Japan in time for the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2020-summer-olympics-p02] Audio manufacturer Audio-Technica was selected by NBC Olympics, a division of the NBC Sports Group, to provide microphone and headphone equipment for production of the Games in partnership with the IOC.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The **2022 Commonwealth Games**, officially known as the **XXII Commonwealth Games** and commonly known as **Birmingham 2022**, were an international multi-sport event for members of the Commonwealth of Nations that took place in Birmingham, England between 28 July and 8 August 2022.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] They were the 22nd edition of the Commonwealth Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] It was the third and seventh time England and the United Kingdom hosted the Commonwealth Games, respectively.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] 4,822 athletes, including 311 para athletes from 72 Commonwealth Games Associations took part in the event.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The event took place at 15 venues across Birmingham, West Midlands and London and featured 19 Commonwealth sports.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] It was also the first major multi-sport event to have more events for women than men and had the largest integrated para-sport programme in the history of the Commonwealth Games with 8 para sports.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] Australia topped the medal table by both total golds (67) and total medals (179), with host nation England finishing second with 58 golds and 176 total medals and Canada finishing third with 26 golds and 92 total medals.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] India finished fourth with 22 gold and 61 total medals, and New Zealand finished fifth with 20 gold and 49 total medals.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] Niue won its first ever Commonwealth Games medal.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] Birmingham was announced as the host city on 21 December 2017.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The event marked the last time that the Commonwealth Games were held under Queen Elizabeth II prior to her death on 8 September of that year, which was exactly one month after the conclusion of the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The event contributed £1.2 billion to the economy of the United Kingdom.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] Two cities initially launched bids for the games: Durban, South Africa, and Edmonton, Canada.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] Edmonton withdrew its bid in February 2015, leaving Durban as the only bid to go forward to CGF General Assembly in September 2015.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] Durban initially secured the right to host the games, as they were the sole bidder for the event.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The city previously considered bidding for the 2020 or 2024 Summer Olympics, but later dropped the idea as it wanted to focus on the 2022 Commonwealth Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] It would have marked the first time the games were held in Africa and the second time a Commonwealth republic would have hosted, following Delhi, India, in 2010.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The games were set to open on 18 July 2022, coinciding with the birthday of the late South African president, Nelson Mandela.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] It was reported in February 2017 that Durban might be unable to host the games due to financial constraints.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] This was confirmed one month later on 13 March 2017 when the CGF stripped Durban of their rights to host the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The bidding process for the 2022 Commonwealth Games was relaunched in March 2017 where English cities Birmingham and Liverpool expressed their interests in hosting the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] On 14 March 2017, Manchester also expressed an interest in hosting the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] By April 2017, the British Government asked city councils to submit proposals for hosting the 2022 Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] Only Birmingham and Liverpool submitted official applications to the Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] London declined to bid, as it was focusing its efforts on preparing for the World Athletics and Para Athletics Championships.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] On 27 April 2017, Manchester City Council announced that Manchester would not bid for the Games but could co-host the Games with other English cities.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] In early September 2017, Birmingham was selected over Liverpool for the recommended bid for England.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The CGF announced that the deadline for the submission of bids was 30 September 2017 and its executive board was expected to announce the host by the end of 2017.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] Commonwealth Games England submitted the Birmingham bid before the deadline to the CGF to host the 2022 Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] However, it was announced that the bid was not fully compliant, and the bidding process was extended until 30 November 2017.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The CGF had 170 questions regarding Birmingham's bid.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] On 21 December 2017, Birmingham was awarded for the 2022 Games as Durban's replacement host.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] Louise Martin, president of the CGF, made the official announcement at a press conference at the Arena Academy in Birmingham.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The Birmingham Organising Committee for the 2022 Commonwealth Games (BOCCG) was responsible for the planning and operational delivery of the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] This includes sport, venue and competition management, ticket sales, all ceremonies and the Queen's Baton Relay.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The headquarters of the organising committee is located in One Brindleyplace building and has taken up the office until December 2022.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] In March 2018, the BOCCG paid £25 million ($35 million) fee to the CGF for the right to host the 2022 Commonwealth Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The fee included the £20 million ($28 million) for the Games hosting charges and £5 million ($7 million) for the development work in the Commonwealth.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] In July 2018, British Prime Minister Theresa May appointed John Crabtree as Chair of the BOCCG.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] In January 2019, Ian Reid was announced as chief executive officer of the BOCCG.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The bill received royal assent and was passed into law as the Birmingham Commonwealth Games Act 2020 on 25 June 2020.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] All athletes and officials are required to test negative for COVID-19 on a PCR test before departure and upon arrival; infections during the Games will be handled on a case-by-case basis, with athletes not necessarily required to withdraw or publicly disclose their infection.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] Commonwealth Games Australia considered the protocols to be less stringent and more "relaxed" than expected, and stated that it planned to impose stricter biosecurity protocols on its athletes to ensure their safety.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The 2022 Commonwealth Games took place in 15 venues spread across the West Midlands region, with seven of them, including the athletics stadium and marathon route, located in the city of Birmingham.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The National Exhibition Centre complex, located on the fringes of the city in neighbouring Solihull, hosted events in its exhibition halls and at the Resorts World Arena.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The six other regional hosts were Coventry, Cannock Chase, Royal Leamington Spa, Sandwell, Warwick and Wolverhampton.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] A sixteenth venue, the Lee Valley VeloPark in Stratford, East London, hosted the track cycling.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] Perry Barr was selected to be the site of the athlete's village, with plans made to demolish the former Birmingham City University campus after the university had moved to a new campus.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The new village was supposed to house up to 6,500 athletes and officials during the games and then become 1,400 new homes after the games, as part of a wider regeneration effort.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] Because of the COVID-19 pandemic, construction of the village fell significantly behind schedule but the games' dates were not pushed back to accommodate this.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] Because the village would not be ready in time for the games, on 11 August 2020 the BOCCG announced that the athletes and team officials will be housed in three 'campus' villages close to competition venues at the University of Birmingham, the University of Warwick, and the NEC.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] Around 1,600 athletes and officials were set to be accommodated at the NEC campus, 1,900 at the University of Warwick campus, and 2,800 at the University of Birmingham campus.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] In 2023, a year after the games had taken place and the first of the village's housing had been finished, the site was still uninhabited and described as a 'ghost village'.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] In 2024, two years after the games, the council announced that it was going to sell a majority of the homes to a private developer - with a total loss of £320m expected.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The large losses from the village will compound on the council's existing financial troubles.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The A34 flyover in Perry Barr was demolished in favour of a dual carriageway at ground level, cycle path and improved public transport services which were approved by Birmingham City Council in October 2019 under its £27.1 million scheme.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] Transport for West Midlands (TfWM) anticipated acute transport challenges across the region, including disruption from redistribution of traffic flows and therefore implemented intensive mobile CCTV monitoring and rapid response capabilities.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The city council announced in January 2020 that the existing National Express Bus Depot in Perry Barr would be demolished as the depot site would be used to construct the phase two of the athletes' village.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] A replacement depot will be constructed on a largely council-owned land on nearby Aston Lane, at a cost of £16 million, eight times the original estimate.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The University railway station, which serves the University of Birmingham, was planned to be renovated and was expected to be complete in time for the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The station would make way for the University of Birmingham, which was due to host hockey and squash events for the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The new station was not finished in time for the event.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The Perry Barr railway station building was rebuilt and the platforms renovated as part of the £30.9 million project in Perry Barr and opened on May 29, 2022.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] TfWM was scheduled to provide the city's first continuous cross-city bus route in time for the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The new Sprint bus route was to run an express service along the A34 and A45 between Walsall and Birmingham Airport and Solihull to Walsall via the city centre.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The service will be zero-emission with priority signals and extended bus lanes, along with "a swift boarding experience" to improve journey times and reliability.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] As of November 2023, the service has yet to commence running.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] At the time of submission of the bid to the CGF, the bid committee announced that the event would cost £750 million.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] On 25 June 2019, the British Government announced that the event costed £778 million.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The British Government covered 75% (£594 million) and Birmingham City Council covered the remaining 25% (£184 million).
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The budget is lower than the £967 million spent on the Gold Coast 2018, but higher than the £543 million spent on the Glasgow 2014.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] It is set to be the most expensive sporting event in the UK since the 2012 Summer Olympics in London which cost £8.8 billion.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The real cost will be published after completion.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] Over 1.3 million tickets were sold for the 2022 Commonwealth Games, which made the event the most attended Commonwealth Games ever to take place in the United Kingdom.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] A ticket ballot for local residents opened on 14 July 2021, with the main public ticket ballot running from 8 to 30 September 2021.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The West Midlands Police said around 3,000 officers would be deployed to patrol the 2022 Commonwealth Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] 1,000 of these were to come from West Midlands Police and 2000 from a "mutual aid" arrangement with other UK forces.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] Additionally, private drones were banned over a no-fly zone and 55 police dogs were also part of the security plan.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The 2022 Commonwealth Games was accompanied by a six-month long cultural event called the Birmingham 2022 Festival.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] It had been billed as "the biggest celebration of creativity ever seen in the region" and was taking place in the host city and throughout the West Midlands.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] With more than 200 events planned, it was one of the biggest cultural programmes ever hosted during the Commonwealth Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] Events took place before and after the 2022 Games, which took place between July 28 and August 8, 2022, from March to September 2022.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The Queen's baton of the 2022 Commonwealth Games was unveiled 29 September 2021.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] Designed as a collaboration between Birmingham Open Media, Raymont-Osman Product Design, Maokwo and Kajul, it is constructed using lost-wax casting, 3D Printing, copper plating and CNC machining.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] It incorporates copper, aluminium, and brass metals symbolising medals, and a strip of platinum in observance of the Queen's Platinum Jubilee.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] It also contains a 360-degree camera, an LED lighting system tied to a heart rate monitor (and displaying different effects when held by two people), and sensors to record environmental conditions—whose data will be analysed by a team at the University of Birmingham following the relay.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The relay began on 7 October 2021 at Buckingham Palace in London, and lasted for 294 days—travelling through 72 Commonwealth nations and territories.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] After placing her message inside the baton, Queen Elizabeth II presented it to British Paralympic athlete and cyclist Kadeena Cox.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] During the opening ceremony, the baton was delivered to Charles, Prince of Wales, who read the Queen's message to officially open the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The opening ceremony of the 2022 Commonwealth Games were held at Alexander Stadium on the evening of 28 July 2022.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] Director Iqbal Khan stated that the ceremony would aim to showcase the "vivid and vibrant confidence" of Birmingham.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] It was headlined by Birmingham-based new wave band Duran Duran, while Tony Iommi of Black Sabbath–who is also a Birmingham native–performed alongside Soweto Kinch during a segment of the ceremony.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The grand finale featured a surprise appearance by Ozzy Osbourne in his first live performance in three years, joined by Tony Iommi and former touring members of Black Sabbath Tommy Clufetos and Adam Wakeman for a medley of "Iron Man" and "Paranoid".
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] All 72 Commonwealth Games Associations sent athletes to the 2022 Commonwealth Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] A new edition of the Commonwealth Games Charter came into effect for these Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The charter also mandates that a number of parasports events (i.e. sports for elite athletes with disabilities) must be integrated within four core sports: athletics, lawn bowls, swimming and weightlifting (the lattermost is actually represented by a variation of powerlifting).
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] This same rule also establishes that the following events for athletes with disabilities are optional: wheelchair basketball (3x3), para track-cycling, para-table tennis and para-triathlon.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] Including compulsory and optional sports (disciplines), there shall be no more than 4 team sports on the programme of a Commonwealth Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] If basketball (3x3) is selected from the pool of optional sports, basketball (wheelchair para 3x3) becomes an obligatory event (or vice versa), in which case the sport of basketball shall be considered as one team sport.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] In cases when cricket is selected from the pool of optional sports, wheelchair basketball also becomes a part of the programme and can be an exception to the 4 team sports limit.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] Respecting local demands, an extra sport or some extra events can be included in this list, but they have to be approved by the Commonwealth Games Federation two years before that edition is held.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The current rules also determine gender parity, whereby men and women have an equal (or broadly equal) share of events.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] On 22 December 2017, the BBC reported that the organisers of the games were in talks with the International Cricket Council (ICC) about the inclusion of women's cricket.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] In November 2018, the ICC confirmed that they have submitted a bid to include women's cricket in the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The bid was made in partnership with the England and Wales Cricket Board (ECB).
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] It was also reported that shooting was likely to be excluded from the games citing a lack of facilities around Birmingham.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] Shooting has been included at every Commonwealth Games since Christchurch 1974.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] In January 2018, the dropping of shooting from the games programme was confirmed by the then CEO of the CGF David Grevemberg.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] In December 2018, The International Shooting Sport Federation (ISSF) delegation including President of ISSF Vladimir Lisin and CEO of British Shooting (BS) Hamish McInnes visited Birmingham and discussed with the Birmingham organising committee to add shooting in the 2022 Commonwealth Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] In December 2018, the World Archery Federation (WA) confirmed that they had delivered a proposal for archery's inclusion in the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The bid was made in partnership with Archery GB and included Aston Hall as a suggested competition venue.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] In June 2019, after some time of popular searches and queries.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] Birmingham organising committee recommended the addition of two extra sports: para table tennis and beach volleyball.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The proposal was approved by the CGF executive board.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The CGF officially announced on 13 August 2019 that the women's T20 cricket, beach volleyball and para table tennis have been included in the Games while due to infrastructure and logistics issues shooting had to be excluded and the proposal to add archery was rejected.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] With the changes in the Charter, and the review of options, the major changes from Gold Coast 2018 include the addition of judo to the core sports and the local organizers' optional decision to hold a women's cricket tournament, taking advantage of local infrastructure.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] Returning to the Games for the first time in 24 years, due to various calendar issues, the cricket event was exclusively female for the first time.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] First time events introduced at Birmingham 2022 are 3x3 basketball and its wheelchair counterpart.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] Birmingham will have the largest number of events available for women and athletes with disabilities in the history of the Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] On 27 October 2020, the list of events to be held in Birmingham was revealed with 271 finals scheduled for 19 sports.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] However, due to the low number of athletes registered in 15 events in 5 sports, they were in risk to be dropped and could not yet be confirmed on that exact time.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] However, with the exception of the 3 relays planned in Paralympic sports, all were confirmed in 2021, giving a total of 283.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The final program was completed with 283 finals scheduled across 20 sports.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] This includes 136 events for women and 134 for men, an unprecedented gender balance amongst major multi-sport events though falling short of the 2018 Commonwealth Games when a perfect gender split had been achieved.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] In addition, 10 mixed gender events and 35 parasport events were held.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] In January 2020, the Indian Olympic Association (IOA), which functions also as the Commonwealth Games Association (CGA) representing India, submitted a proposal to the CGF to host a combined archery and shooting championships in Chandigarh during January 2022.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The proposal was endorsed by the National Rifle Association of India (NRAI), the Government of India, the ISSF and WA.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The CGF Executive Board approved the proposal at their meeting in London which took place on 21–23 February 2020, and also confirmed that the 2022 Commonwealth Shooting and Archery Championships and the 2022 Commonwealth Games will be two separately organised and funded Commonwealth Sport events.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The CGF shall issue a medal table one week following the Birmingham 2022 closing ceremony that includes results from Chandigarh 2022 as a further and final ranking of competing nations and territories from the respective competitions.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] In July 2021, the CGF announced that the event had been cancelled due to the COVID-19 pandemic in India.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] In February 2022, the CGF announced that esports would be included in the Games as a demonstration event and is in a possibility to be added at the games program at the future editions.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The inaugural Commonwealth Esports Championships had separate branding, medals, and organisation and included both men and women's *Dota 2*, *eFootball*, and *Rocket League* events.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] On 14 July 2023, the Nigerian team was disqualified as winners of the women's 4x100 metre relay in athletics as Nzubechi Grace Nwokocha was found in violation of anti-doping measures.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] This promoted England to gold, Jamaica to silver, and Australia were awarded bronze.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The official emblem was unveiled on 27 July 2019 at Centenary Square during the Commonwealth Social festival.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] It was designed by local agency RBL, based in Royal Leamington Spa, and is a jagged, triangular "B" shape formed by blue-yellow gradient lines representing the key venues of the Games in the West Midlands.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The emblem is also the first to use the new branding for the CGF, as "Commonwealth Sport".
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] It received a mainly positive reaction from locals in the city and on social media and some compared it to the emblem for the 2012 Summer Olympics and Paralympics.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The official sponsors of the 2022 Commonwealth Games were Longines, University of Birmingham, E.ON, Chase, Severn Trent and Reckitt.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The official mascot for the Birmingham 2022 Commonwealth Games is Perry, a multi-coloured bull.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] Perry is named after an area of Birmingham, Perry Barr, within which Perry Park and the main athletics stadium, the Alexander Stadium, are located.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The bull has a long history with being a symbol of Birmingham, and was positively received by the public on launch.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] Perry was designed by ten-year-old Emma Lou from Bolton.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] Perry was reproduced in coloured willow in a Birmingham 2022 display commemorating the games at the Chelsea Flower Show in 2022.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] In July 2020, production company Sunset+Vine was appointed as the host broadcaster for the event.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] In October 2020, BBC acquired the United Kingdom rights.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] A record 57.1 million streams were generated on the BBC digital platforms by coverage of the 2022 Commonwealth Games, breaking the previous Commonwealth Games record.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] Additionally, the number of streams from the previous Commonwealth Games was more than six times higher than it was with this figure.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] The last event in 2018 took place in Australia, which is in a completely different time zone.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] 28.6 million people watched 2022 Commonwealth Games on the BBC's linear channels in total.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] Prior to the women's 100-metre backstroke and men's 100-metre breaststroke finals, viewership peaked at 6.6 million viewers, while the opening ceremony attracted a five-minute audience peak of 5.2 million.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] Audiences peaked at 5.1 million for the women's 4 x 400-metre relay final, while 4.8 million watched the closing ceremony.
[src:3x3-basketball/2022-commonwealth-games] Other notable moments of the BBC's coverage included 4.2 million people watching the men's 200-metre final and 4.1 million people watching Adam Peaty win the 50-metre breaststroke final.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] 3x3 has been a basketball format long played in streets and gyms across the world, albeit in a less formal way.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] Starting in the late 2000s, 3x3 game rules started to become standardized throughout the United States, most notably through the Gus Macker and Hoop It Up tournament series, which held large events across the country that included teams and players from all skill levels.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] In 1992, Adidas launched its now-discontinued streetball competition.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] Since then, the number of 3x3 events and competitions has been steadily growing around the world.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] A Romanian organization, Sport Arena Streetball, began hosting 3x3 events in Bucharest as early as 2005, helping to grow the sport locally and regionally before formal FIBA rules were introduced.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] FIBA first test 3x3 at the 2007 Asian Indoor Games in Macau, followed by further test events in April 2008 in the Dominican Republic and October 2008 in Indonesia.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] The international debut of 3x3 under FIBA rules occurred at the 2009 Asian Youth Games, where 19 teams competed in the boys' tournament and 16 teams competed in the girls' tournament, with all games held at Anglican High School in Tanah Merah, Singapore.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] 3x3 made its worldwide competitive debut at the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics in Singapore, where 20 teams competed in both boys' and girls' categories, with games held at the Youth Space.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] Since then, FIBA has regularly held world championships in both open and U18 categories.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] Bucharest, later called the "Mecca of 3x3 basketball" by Sports Illustrated, hosted the first FIBA Europe 3x3 Championships in 2014, an event that helped establish organized 3x3 competition across Europe.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] In subsequent years, the city also hosted international 3x3 tournaments, attracting teams from outside Europe.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] FIBA developed 3x3 as a standalone discipline with its own format and regular international competitions.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball made its Olympic debut at the 2020 Summer Olympics in Tokyo.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] The 3x3 basketball variation has also been used in several tournaments, such as the Nike 3ON3 Tournament and Spokane Hoopfest, the largest 3x3 basketball tournament in the world, held annually in Spokane, Washington.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] FIBA releases from time-to-time a supplement to its official basketball rules specifically for 3x3.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] The rules state that regular FIBA rules apply to all situations not specifically addressed in the FIBA 3x3 rules.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] The current set, both in an abbreviated version and longer format, was published in August 2019.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] The current rules depart from regular full-court basketball in the following ways.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] Each team consists of three players and one substitute.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] Each team must have three players on the court when the game begins.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] The game is played on a half-court with one basket.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] The American NBA & WNBA standard half-court distance is 15.24 m (50 ft) wide & 14.33 m (47 ft) long.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] The ball is the size of a size 6 basketball (720 mm, 28.5 in) as used in the women's full-court game and its mass is that of the size 7 standard (620 g, 22 oz) used in the men's full-court game.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] A coin toss is held immediately before the game, and the winning team of the coin flip can choose to take possession of the ball at the start of the game, or take the first possession of a potential overtime period.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] In turn, this means that if the game goes into overtime, the first possession goes to the team that started the game on defense.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] The game begins with the defensive team passing the ball to the offensive team to signify the start of the game.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] All offensive players must begin outside of the arc (the opposite side of the arc of the net), and the defensive team must begin inside of the arc.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] Once the offensive team receives the ball, the clock starts.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] This exchange is also used to restart the game from any dead ball situation.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] The game is a single period of a maximum 10 minutes and the winner is the first team to score 21 or the team with the higher score at the end of the 10 minutes; scoring 21 points immediately ends the game.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] Every successful shot inside the arc, including free throws, is awarded one point, while every successful shot outside of the arc ("downtown") is awarded two points.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] After a made goal or free throw (except for technical or unsportsmanlike fouls and team fouls 10 or more; see below), play restarts with a player from the non-scoring team taking the ball directly under the basket and then dribbling or passing it to a point behind the arc.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] The defense is not allowed to play for the ball inside the block/charge semi-circle under the basket.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] In any held-ball situation, the defensive team is granted possession.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] The offensive team must attempt a shot for a goal within 12 seconds.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] An offensive player may also not dribble inside the arc with their back or side to the basket for more than 3 consecutive seconds.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] For either violation the defensive team is granted possession.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] There is a Trent Tucker Rule in which with up to 0.2 seconds left in regulation or on the shot clock, a high lob, or tip-in must be made.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] A tie in regulation time leads to an untimed overtime period, after a one-minute intermission.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] Whichever team began the game as the defensive team, begins overtime as the offensive team.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] The first team to score two points wins the game.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] Note: if a game is tied at 20 at the end of regulation, a team scoring their 21st point in overtime does not end the game.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] Substitutions can occur only in a dead-ball situation; a substitute can only enter from behind the end line opposite the basket, and the substitution becomes official once the player leaving the game has "tagged up" by making physical contact with the substitute.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] Each team is allowed one 30 second time-out per game.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] Each personal or technical foul counts as one team foul, while each unsportsmanlike or disqualifying foul counts as two team fouls.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] Personal fouls during the act of shooting inside the arc are awarded one free throw, while fouls during the act of shooting behind the arc and the shot is unsuccessful are awarded two free throws.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] Team fouls 7, 8 and 9 are awarded two free throws, and all team fouls thereafter are awarded two free throws and possession of the ball.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] The "bonus" rule specifically supersedes the normal rule for fouls in the act of shooting.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] The un-timed overtime period is considered extension of regulation for purpose of team fouls.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] The first unsportsmanlike foul against a player results in two free throws.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] A second unsportsmanlike foul, or a disqualifying foul, results in two free throws and possession.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] A player who commits two unsportsmanlike fouls is disqualified.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] A team loses the game by default if all of its players are disqualified.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] All technical fouls result in one free throw, with possession going to the team that was entitled to possession at that time.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] If a foul is committed that results in the non-fouling team retaining possession, i.e. a technical or "unsportsmanlike" foul, the non-fouling team will receive the exchange outside of the arc.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] Offensive fouls, if not technical, unsportsmanlike, or disqualifying, never result in free throws, regardless of the number of team fouls.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] In the case of a double foul, no free throws are awarded to either team, regardless of team foul count or whether the double fouls were unsportsmanlike.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] FIBA sees 3x3 as a major vehicle for promotion of the game of basketball throughout the world.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] FIBA Secretary General and IOC member Patrick Baumann explained: "The 3x3 concept has all the elements and skills required for basketball, it has inspired and will continue to inspire many great players in the future.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] At the same time, it is the easiest and one of the most-effective ways to bring youngsters to basketball, keep them and promote our game.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] FIBA is pursuing a strategy to implement 3x3.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] FIBA has developed a digital community that acts as a repository for all FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events worldwide and offers all players an individual world ranking based on the points earned by players at FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] Any event around the world can become FIBA-endorsed by using FIBA's freeware, EventMaker, to organise the event.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] All FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events are classified within an established competition hierarchy, thus forming an official competition network.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] The pinnacle of this competition network is the FIBA 3x3 World Tour, which includes a series of World Tour Masters and one Final.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] A team can qualify for a World Tour Masters by playing in any of the designated World Tour qualifiers.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] The North American National Basketball Association (NBA) has also embraced 3x3.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] Since 2016, the NBA has held a summer series of tournaments known as "Dew NBA 3X", where local amateur players from around the US compete in regional events for cash prizes and a finals berth.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] The men's and women's NBA 3X champions then advance to the USA Basketball national 3x3 championship to potentially represent their country internationally.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] These tournaments also include live music performances, 3-point shooting contests for fans, an *NBA 2K* eSports competition, and appearances from current NBA players.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] The qualification system for the FIBA 3x3 World Cups for men and women differs radically from the system used for FIBA full-court competitions.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] According to *The New York Times*, 3x3 has "an unusual qualifying system designed to grow the sport all year long as much as find the best teams for the World Cup." National team entries are based strictly on a country's official 3x3 ranking.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] The ranking system for national teams also considers individual player rankings.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] For example, the US women's team qualified for the 2018 World Cup while the men's team did not, even though the men were ranked higher than the women on the cutoff date.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] Participating in a FIBA-sanctioned 3x3 event can earn ranking points; according to a FIBA executive, "Andorra has heavy participation every weekend." The current concentration of ranking events in Europe makes it more difficult for non-European nations, especially the US, to qualify.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] The aforementioned FIBA executive, when asked about the prospect of the 2020 Olympic debut of 3x3 potentially lacking any participation from the US, admitted that "a lot of teams want to beat the US.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] After the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics, FIBA established a regular World Cup that always includes men and women competing simultaneously in open, U23 and U18 categories.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] World Cups are played every year, except in years when there are Youth Olympic Games or Olympic Games.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] The COVID-19 pandemic caused the cancellation of the 2020 event.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] Classification to the World Cup is based on the 3x3 Federation Ranking, which ranks all National Federations based on the 3x3 Individual World Ranking points of their top 100 nationals in the respective category (i.e. men, women, U23 men, U23 women, U18 men, and U18 women).
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball became a regular European Games contest since its introduction at the 2015 European Games in Baku, Azerbaijan.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball made a debut in Olympic programme for the 2020 Summer Olympics in Tokyo, Japan, for both men and women.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball was included in 2022 Commonwealth Games in Birmingham, England.
[src:3x3-basketball/3x3-basketball] After the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, FIBA banned Russian teams and officials from participating in FIBA 3x3 Basketball competitions.
